{{short description| Fungal members of the plankton communities of aquatic ecosystems }} [[File:Morelasci.jpg|thumb|Marine Ascomycete fungus]] '''Mycoplankton''' are [[saprotrophic nutrition|saprotropic]] members of the [[plankton]] communities of [[Marine biology|marine]] and [[Limnology|freshwater]] [[Aquatic ecosystem|ecosystems]].<ref>Jones, E.B.G., Hyde, K.D., & Pang, K.-L., eds. (2014). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=mXfnBQAAQBAJ Freshwater fungi: and fungal-like organisms]''. Berlin/Boston: De Gruyter.</ref><ref>{{cite book |year=2012 |editor1-last=Jones |editor1-first=E.B.G. |editor1-link= |editor2-last=Pang |editor2-first=K.-L. |editor2-link= |display-editors= |title=Marine Fungi, and Fungal-like Organisms |url=http://www.degruyter.com/view/product/177990 |deadurl= |format= |type= |series=Marine and Freshwater Botany |edition= |location=Berlin, Boston |publisher=De Gruyter |publication-date=August 2012 |isbn=978-3-11-026406-7 |access-date=September 3, 2015 |ref=jones2012 }}</ref> They are composed of [[Filamentous fungus|filamentous]] free-living [[Fungus|fungi]] and yeasts that are associated with planktonic particles or [[phytoplankton]].<ref name=":2" /> Similar to [[bacterioplankton]], these aquatic fungi play a significant role in [[heterotroph]]ic [[mineralization (soil science)|mineralization]] and [[nutrient cycling]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wang |first1=G. |last2=Wang |first2=X. |last3=Liu |first3=X. |last4=Li |first4=Q. |editor-last=Raghukumar |editor-first=C. |title=Biology of marine fungi |location=Berlin, Heidelberg |publisher=Springer-Verlag |year=2012 |pages=71–88 |chapter=Diversity and biogeochemical function of planktonic fungi in the ocean |isbn=978-3-642-23341-8 |url=https://www.springer.com/us/book/9783642233418 |access-date=September 3, 2015 |doi=10.1007/978-3-642-23342-5 }}</ref> Mycoplankton can be up to 20&nbsp;mm in diameter and over 50&nbsp;mm in length.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Fungi and Macroaggregation in Deep-Sea Sediments|journal = Microbial Ecology|date = 2007-11-11|issn = 0095-3628|pages = 168–177|volume = 56|issue = 1|doi = 10.1007/s00248-007-9334-y|pmid = 17994287|first = Samir|last = Damare|first2 = Chandralata|last2 = Raghukumar}}</ref>
In a typical milliliter of seawater, there are approximately 10<sup>3</sup> to 10<sup>4</sup> fungal cells.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Seaweed resistance to microbial attack: A targeted chemical defense against marine fungi|url = http://www.pnas.org/content/100/12/6916|journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|date = 2003-06-10|issn = 0027-8424|pmc = 165804|pmid = 12756301|pages = 6916–6921|volume = 100|issue = 12|doi = 10.1073/pnas.1131855100|first = Julia|last = Kubanek|first2 = Paul R.|last2 = Jensen|first3 = Paul A.|last3 = Keifer|first4 = M. Cameron|last4 = Sullards|first5 = Dwight O.|last5 = Collins|first6 = William|last6 = Fenical}}</ref> This number is greater in coastal ecosystems and [[Estuary|estuaries]] due to nutritional runoff from terrestrial communities. The greatest diversity and number of species of mycoplankton is found in [[Coastal ecosystems|surface waters]] (< 1000 m), and the [[Water column|vertical profile]] depends on the abundance of [[phytoplankton]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|title = Molecular characterization of the spatial diversity and novel lineages of mycoplankton in Hawaiian coastal waters|url = http://www.nature.com/ismej/journal/v4/n1/full/ismej200987a.html|journal = The ISME Journal|date = 2009-07-30|issn = 1751-7362|pages = 111–120|volume = 4|issue = 1|doi = 10.1038/ismej.2009.87|pmid = 19641535|first = Zheng|last = Gao|first2 = Zackary I.|last2 = Johnson|first3 = Guangyi|last3 = Wang}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Identification of Habitat-Specific Biomes of Aquatic Fungal Communities Using a Comprehensive Nearly Full-Length 18S rRNA Dataset Enriched with Contextual Data|journal = PLoS ONE|date = 2015-07-30|pmc = 4520555|pmid = 26226014|pages = e0134377|volume = 10|issue = 7|doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0134377|first = Katrin|last = Panzer|first2 = Pelin|last2 = Yilmaz|first3 = Michael|last3 = Weiß|first4 = Lothar|last4 = Reich|first5 = Michael|last5 = Richter|first6 = Jutta|last6 = Wiese|first7 = Rolf|last7 = Schmaljohann|first8 = Antje|last8 = Labes|first9 = Johannes F.|last9 = Imhoff}}</ref> Furthermore, this difference in distribution may vary between seasons due to nutrient availability.<ref name=":3">GUTIERREZ, Marcelo H; PANTOJA, Silvio; QUINONES, Renato A and GONZALEZ, Rodrigo R. First record of flamentous fungi in the coastal upwelling ecosystem off central Chile. ''Gayana (Concepc.)'' [online]. 2010, vol.74, n.1, pp. 66-73. ISSN 0717-6538. </ref> Aquatic fungi survive in a constant [[oxygen deficient environment]], and therefore depend on oxygen diffusion by [[turbulence]] and oxygen generated by [[Phototroph|photosynthetic organisms]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title = Plankton Dynamics of Indian Waters|last = Sridhar|first = K.R.|publisher = Pratiksha Publications|year = 2009|isbn = |location = Jaipur, India|pages = 133–148|chapter = 10. Aquatic fungi – Are they planktonic?}}</ref>
Aquatic fungi can be classified using three groups:<ref name=":0" /> * '''Lower fungi''' - adapted to marine habitats ([[Zoospore|zoosporic]] fungi, including mastigomycetes: [[oomycete]]s & [[chytridiomycetes]]) * '''Higher fungi''' -filamentous, modified to planktonic lifestyle ([[hyphomycetes]], [[Ascomycota|ascomycetes]], [[Basidiomycota|basidiomycetes]]) * '''Terrestrial fungi''' - contain appendages of marine fungi ([[trichomycetes]]) The majority of mycoplankton species are higher fungi, found in the [[Ascomycota]] and [[Basidiomycota]] phylums.<ref name=":1" />
According to fossil records, fungi date back to the late [[Proterozoic]] era, 900-570 million years ago. It is hypothesized that mycoplankton evolved from terrestrial fungi, likely in the [[Paleozoic]] era (390 million years ago).<ref>{{Cite book|title = Marine Fungi: and Fungal-like Organisms|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=RcF97cHppPsC|publisher = Walter de Gruyter|date = 2012-08-31|isbn = 9783110264067|first = E. B. Gareth|last = Jones|first2 = Ka-Lai|last2 = Pang}}</ref> The methods and pathways of terrestrial fungi's adaption to the marine environment are still under study.
== Biogeochemical Contributions == The primary role of all fungi is to degrade detrital [[organic matter]] from plants,<ref>Carlile MJ, Watkinson SC, Gooday GW (2001) The fungi. San Diego: Academic Press.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Molecular approaches for assessing fungal diversity in marine substrata|url = http://www.degruyter.com/view/j/bot.2005.48.issue-5/bot.2005.046/bot.2005.046.xml|journal = Botanica Marina|volume = 48|issue = 5–6|doi = 10.1515/bot.2005.046|first = Ka-Lai|last = Pang|first2 = Julian I.|last2 = Mitchell|year = 2005}}</ref> and mycoplankton is no exception. By working with microbial communities, mycoplankton efficiently converts particulate organic matter to dissolved organic matter as part of the [[Biogeochemical cycle|biogeochemical]] cycle.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Marine snow, organic solute plumes, and optimal chemosensory behavior of bacteria|journal = Limnology and Oceanography|date = 2001-09-01|issn = 1939-5590|pages = 1309–1318|volume = 46|issue = 6|doi = 10.4319/lo.2001.46.6.1309|first = Thomas|last = Kiørboe|first2 = George A.|last2 = Jackson|citeseerx = 10.1.1.570.5719}}</ref> Mycoplankton and heterotrophic bacteria mediate carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, and other nutrient fluxes in marine ecosystems.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Benthic Bacterial and Fungal Productivity and Carbon Turnover in a Freshwater Marsh|url = http://aem.asm.org/content/72/1/596|journal = Applied and Environmental Microbiology|date = 2006-01-01|issn = 0099-2240|pmc = 1352256|pmid = 16391096|pages = 596–605|volume = 72|issue = 1|doi = 10.1128/AEM.72.1.596-605.2006|first = Nanna|last = Buesing|first2 = Mark O.|last2 = Gessner}}</ref> It has been shown that there are higher concentrations of mycoplankton near the surface and in shallow waters, which indicates their connection with the upwelling of organic matter. This further correlates with abundant [[phytoplankton]] communities at the surface, implying that mycoplankton is intimately involved in organic matter consumption in the [[Photic zone|euphotic]] zone.<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|title = Distribution and Diversity of Planktonic Fungi in the West Pacific Warm Pool|doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0101523.s001}}</ref><ref name=":3" />
== See also == * [[Algae]] * [[Bacterioplankton]] * [[Biological pump]] * [[Fungus]] * [[Phytoplankton]] * [[Zooplankton]]
